I"Ì<div style="background-color: #E3F4F4; padding: 15px 15px 15px 15px; border:1px solid black;">
  <b>\(|a - c| \leq |a - b|+|b - c|\) holds for all real numbers \(a\), \(b\) and \(c\).</b>
</div>
<p><br />
This is in a way saying that the distance between \(a\) and \(c\) is less than or equal to the distance from \(a\) to \(b\) and then from \(b\) to \(c\).</p>
<h3>Proof:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
Let $$a$$, $$b$$ and $$c$$ be real numbers. Let $$x = a-b$$ and $$y = b-c$$. Using the triangle inquality we know that
<div>
$$
\begin{align*}
|x + y| &amp;\leq |x| + |y| \\
|a - b + b - c| &amp;\leq |a - b| + |b - c| \\
|a - c| &amp;\leq |a - c| + |c - b|. \\
\end{align*}
$$
</div>
$$\blacksquare$$
<br />
<br />
</h3>
